Off-duty police officers, along with Diallo's friends and relatives, attended the arraignment.
Police Commissioner Safir expressed condolences for Diallo and the officers, emphasizing the need for a fair trial.
The officers believed Diallo was armed, leading to the tragic shooting.
Diallo's family arrived from Guinea seeking justice.
The officers face charges for firing 41 shots at Diallo, who was hit 19 times.
The defense argues the officers thought Diallo was reaching for a gun.
The case highlights the challenges of convicting police officers for on-duty killings.
Diallo's family seeks justice through civil suits and autopsy discrepancies.
